The paper primarily focuses on Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) technologies and their usability and adoption, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The paper also discusses user studies and evaluation research, which falls under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Additionally, the paper discusses demographic biases in participant recruitment, which falls under the category of social and information sciences (cs.SI). The paper also touches upon the topic of cyber threats and vulnerabilities, which falls under the category of cyber security (cs.CY). Finally, the paper discusses the development and proposal of new MFA tools, which falls under the category of software engineering (cs.SE).
